topics.content:
Theory:
Java is a class-based, object-oriented programming language that runs on the Java Virtual Machine (JVM).

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, Java!");
    }
}

Theory:
Java programs must have a class and a main method.

Example:
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Basic Syntax");
    }
}

Theory:
Java supports int, float, double, char, boolean, String.

Example:
int age = 20;
double price = 99.9;
char grade = 'A';
boolean isValid = true;

Theory:
Java has arithmetic, logical, relational, and bitwise operators.

Example:
int a = 10, b = 5;
System.out.println(a + b);

Theory:
Java supports if-else and switch.

Example:
int marks = 80;
if (marks > 75) {
    System.out.println("Distinction");
}

Theory:
Java supports for, while, do-while loops.

Example:
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
}

Theory:
Reusable blocks of code.

Example:
static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

Theory:
Java is object-oriented.

Example:
class Student {
    String name;
}

Theory:
One class inherits another using extends.

Example:
class Animal {}
class Dog extends Animal {}

Theory:
Achieved using abstract classes and interfaces.

Example:
abstract class Car {
    abstract void drive();
}

Theory:
Hide data using private variables.

Example:
class Demo {
    private int x;
}

Theory:
Handle runtime errors using try-catch.

Example:
try {
    int x = 5 / 0;
} catch (Exception e) {
    System.out.println("Error!");
}

Theory:
Run tasks in parallel using Thread.

Example:
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread running");
    }
}
